         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">25, WILTON PLACE. S.W. ¶ London ¶ June 1876 ¶ My dear Sir ¶  ¶ During a short visit I lately paid to Paris ¶  a second box of your Monocotyledons was I am informed sent off to you from Kew and the bil...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">76.06.00</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M3, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Pencilled at top of letter in M's hand: '[Ba]tis, Halorageae Plantagineae (Myriceae Schnizlein)'.</p>
               </note>
               <seg rend="form%20text" style="color: #2f5496; font-family: Times; ">25, WILTON PLACE. S.W.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">London</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">June 1876</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>During a short visit I lately paid to Paris<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bentham was in Paris from 2 to 10 June 1876. On 5 June, he took his seat as <seg style="font-style: italic; ">membre correspondant</seg> at the Académie des Sciences. See B. Jackson (1906), pp. 236-7.</p>
               </note> a second box of your Monocotyledons was I am informed sent off to you from Kew and the bill of lading duly forwarded to you by post.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bill of lading not found.</p>
               </note> I trust you will have received it safely</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Since my return I have done the <name key="Aroideae">Aroideae</name>. I have ascertained that the leaves which Brown mistook for those of <name key="Dracontium">Dracontium</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">R. Brown (1810), p. 337; see comments in Bentham (1863-78), vol. 6, p. 155.</p>
               </note> belong to the <name key="Brachyspatha%20variabilis">Brachyspatha variabilis</name> which is Schultz's n. 562 from Port Darwin — the leaf in your herbarium which you thought might be Brown's plant is I think that of <name key="Tacca%20pinnatifida">Tacca pinnatifida</name> — The leaves of <name key="Dracontium">Dracontium</name> and Brachyspatha are so much alike as to be distinguishable only by a close examination of the venation</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have some difficulty in identifying some of Brown's Monocotyledons from his not having always revised his labels after the publication of the Prodromus<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">R. Brown (1810).</p>
               </note> but with some study I think I clear them up pretty well. Several of his <name key="Eriocaulon">Eriocaulon</name>s are neither in your collection nor in that of Kew<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">The Australian collections of Robert Brown (1773-1858) were at the British Museum.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have a few small families to finish up and in a few days hope to attack the <name key="Restiaceae">Restiaceae</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In the box sent you will find a copy of the new part of Genera Plantarum<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83). Part 2 of vol. 2 was published in May 1876 (TL2).</p>
               </note> I hope some Australian botanists may order the work which is a heavy expense to us</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I trust that by the time you receive this you will have kindly sent off the <name key="Cyperaceae">Cyperaceae</name> and <name key="Gramineae">Gramineae</name> for which I hope to be ready in the course of September</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Yours very truly</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>George Bentham</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Baron F. v. Mueller</p>
